http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/title.value: Montana Standards For Career and Vocational Technical Education

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Career and Vocational/Technical Education is a program of articulated sequential experiences that prepare students for successful participation in community, family, post-secondary education and careers. Career and Vocational/Technical Education programs include Agriculture, Business and Marketing, Family and Consumer Sciences, Industrial Technology, and Trades and Industry. Career and Vocational/Technical Education programs focus on career preparation, resource management, communication, technical skill development, applied academics, technological literacy; and personal skills and leadership. Programs are driven by authentic applications where students will be prepared for the workplace. Through Career and Vocational/Technical Education students are empowered to be successful in today's world.
Students experience various career opportunities and assess personal career pathways.
Benchmark I
describe and demonstrate the importance of goal setting and career planning.
explore and investigate career opportunities.
describe various lifetime roles (e.g., friend, student, leader, worker, family member).
Benchmark II
explore and identify personal interests, aptitudes, and abilities and develop strategies to achieve tentative career goals.
utilize local resources to research career plans.
recognize the interrelationships of family, community, career, and leisure roles.
Benchmark III
develop, evaluate, and modify personal career plans.
experience an internship, job shadow, or work experience related to their career plan.
evaluate career choices and the effect on family and lifestyle.
Students demonstrate an understanding and apply principles of Resource Management (i.e., financial, time, personal management).
Benchmark I
use basic monetary skills, practice maintaining basic financial records.
follow detailed instructions and complete assignment (e.g., project/time management).
recognize time constraints (e.g., personal time).
recognize limitations on physical resources.
Benchmark II
prepare a budget and keep financial records.
prioritize, allocate time, prepare and follow schedules to complete a project.
apply appropriate time to task.
use physical resources wisely to accomplish a goal.
Benchmark III
prepare and analyze financial plans, make forecasts, make adjustments to meet objectives, and evaluate financial records.
select, design, complete and evaluate a project (e.g., manage multiple facets of a project).
manage multiple priorities and assess effectiveness of outcomes (school, work, family).
evaluate the use of physical resources.
Students acquire and utilize personal and leadership skills to become successful, productive citizens.
Benchmark I
serve as a positive role model by following the rules, regulations, and policies of the school community.
identify personal and work ethics.
recognize characteristics of good citizenship.
identify methods that can increase a person's self-esteem.
observe and recognize diversity.
describe several methods of communication.
Benchmark II
demonstrate active leadership skills by participation in group activities and projects.
demonstrate positive personal and work ethics.
demonstrate skills to be a productive citizen.
apply self-esteem building practices.
demonstrate appreciation for diverse perspective needs and characteristics.
practice several methods of effective communication.
Benchmark III
assume a leadership role (e.g., team leader, CTSO officer, committee chair).
evaluate, compare and contrast positive personal and work ethics.
implement and evaluate a successful, productive citizenship activity (i.e., community service project).
select methods to constructively build esteem in others as well as self.
respect differences and works well with individuals from diverse backgrounds and philosophies.
utilize multiple communication methods to complete a class project.
Students acquire and demonstrate current technical skills leading to an occupation.
Benchmark I
identify appropriate technical skills required for selected occupation.
practice safe and appropriate use of technology.
identify and use the appropriate tools and equipment for the task.
identify and demonstrate appropriate care of technological tools.
follow basic technical instruction.
Benchmark II
practice technical skills and procedures required for an occupation.
practice safe and appropriate use of technology.
select the appropriate tools, equipment, and procedures for the task.
manage and maintain technological tools and follow troubleshooting protocol.
apply technical information to a variety of sources.
Benchmark III
master the technical skills required for an entry level job or advanced training.
practice safe and appropriate use of technology.
mastery of tools and equipment needed for an entry level job or advanced training.
manage and maintain technological systems and follow troubleshooting protocol.
adapt technical information generated from a variety of technical sources.
Students know and demonstrate the requirements of the workplace through authentic application.
Benchmark I
apply academic and technical skills to a class project.
identify the concepts of entrepreneurship.
describe how decisions affect self and others.
use acceptable industry standard equipment in a school setting.
Benchmark II
practice and demonstrate academic and technical skills to a workplace setting.
apply the concepts of entrepreneurship.
identify possible outcomes and consequences of decisions.
use acceptable industry standard equipment in a school setting.
Benchmark III
transfer academic and technical skills to the level of industry standards.
evaluate and/or design components of a business plan.
demonstrate decision-making and problem-solving skills.
use acceptable industry standard equipment in a school setting.
